The two Poles
The European Parliament recently condemned the Polish government's attempt to strip Bronislaw Geremek of his parliamentary mandate.
Former leader of Solidarity, former political prisoner, and former Minister of Foreign Affairs - he led Poland's accession to NATO - Geremek refused to sign another new statement claiming he was not a secret police agent during the communist era.
European parliamentarians spoke of a "witch hunt" regarding the behavior of the Polish government, and Geremek stated that the law on decommunization constitutes a threat to public freedoms.
In response, Polish Prime Minister Jaroslaw Kaczynski accused him of "harming the motherland" and of inciting anti-Polish sentiment.
The communists used the same words when Geremek criticized their abuse of power.
A constitutional court decision dated May 11 largely invalidated the cleansing law, allowing Geremek to retain his seat in the European Parliament, at least for now.
But this law fits within the framework of a general policy of the Polish government whose sole purpose is to weaken the country's institutions and democratic fabric.
What is happening in Poland, the country where the collapse of communism began?
Each revolution goes through two phases: first a struggle for freedom, then a fight for power.
The first is the emancipation of the human soul through which man expresses his best, while the second frees the worst: envy, intrigues, greed, suspicion, and the desire for revenge.
The revolution sparked by the Polish trade union Solidarity followed an unusual trajectory.
Solidarity, forced into clandestinity when the state of martial law was declared in December 1981, survived seven years of repression to reappear in the open in 1989, following Gorbachev's "perestroïka."
During the negotiations that ended the communist regime, Solidarity and the reformist wing of the communist government reached an agreement that paved the way for the peaceful dismantling of the communist dictatorship throughout the Soviet bloc.
Solidarity chose a conciliatory attitude rather than revenge, preferring the idea of a Poland for all rather than a divided country between all-powerful winners and oppressed losers.
Since 1989, there have been changes in government, but the country has remained stable. The former communists themselves have accepted the rules of parliamentary democracy and market economy.
But not everyone followed this path.
Today, Poland is governed by a coalition of post-Solidarity revenge-seekers, post-communist provincial agitators, xenophobic and antisemitic groups, heirs to pre-war chauvinism, and circles surrounding Radio Maryja, the voice of ethno-clerical fundamentalism.
One sees everywhere alarming signs: the authority of the judiciary is undermined, the independence of the constitutional court is called into question, civil servants are being bought, and the role of the prosecutor is being politicized.
Every day, social life undergoes repressive regulation.
Why all of this?
Every successful revolution has its winners and losers.
The Polish revolution brought about public freedoms, but also increased crime, a market economy, as well as the risk of bankruptcy for businesses and high unemployment, along with the emergence of a dynamic middle class, accompanied by a widening income gap.
She opened Poland to Europe, but she also instilled the fear of the foreigner and the fear of a mass Western cultural invasion.
For the losers of the 1989 Polish revolution, freedom comes with a lot of uncertainties.
In large companies, workers of Solidarity have become the victims of the freedoms they have won.
In the communist prison universe, people were considered to belong to the state, but the latter took care of them.
In a world of freedom, there is no one to take care of us.
It is in this atmosphere of anxiety that the current coalition governs, combining George Bush's conservative remedy with Vladimir Putin's centralism.
The Solidarity veterans thought that the end of the dictatorship would allow them to reach the heavens.
But the guilty among the communists were not punished, and the virtuous militants of Solidarity were not rewarded.
Thus, the feeling of injustice gave rise to resentment, envy, and a vengeful energy directed both against old enemies and former friends who seemed to be getting by with ease.
The losers did not want to acknowledge that the conquest of freedom was the greatest success of Poland in 300 years.
For them, Poland remained a country governed by the communist security apparatus.
This Poland was in need of a moral revolution that would ensure that crimes would not go unpunished, virtue would be rewarded, and injustices would be rectified.
After their victory in the 2005 general elections, the defeated political parties chose a method: a major purge.
According to the initial estimates, the cleansing process should take 17 years and affect 700,000 people.
A list of names was found in the archives of the security services; it will be made public.
And the 700,000 people promised the lustration must declare that they did not collaborate with the security services.
Those who refuse or make a false declaration must be dismissed and banned from practicing their profession for ten years.
