Cardinal Dziwisz of Kraków reminds us that there is no room "for revenge, vengeance, disrespect for human dignity, and unfounded accusations."
Never since the fall of communism has a cardinal used such strong words.
Should this purification have taken place at the beginning of Poland's transformation? The goal of this peaceful revolution was freedom, sovereignty, and economic reforms, not a hunt for suspected, confirmed or not, individuals who had belonged to the secret police.
If this hunt had been organized in 1990, neither the economic reforms of Leszek Balcerowicz nor the establishment of the rule of law would have been possible.
And Poland would not be a member of NATO or the European Union.
Today, two Poles face each other.
The Poland of suspicion, fear, and revenge fights the Poland of hope, courage, and dialogue.
This Poland — made of openness and tolerance, that of John Paul II and Czesław Miłosz, of my friends from the underground and from prison — must prevail.
I believe the Poles will once again defend their right to be treated with dignity.
The decision of the constitutional tribunal offers hope that the second phase of the Polish revolution will not destroy either what gave it birth, the desire for freedom, or what it has produced, a democratic state.
